Verifying Rearranged Parcel Labels

A logistics coordinator in Chennai receives two parcel label strings, s and t. Before dispatch, the coordinator must verify whether both labels contain exactly the same characters with the same frequencies, even if their order is different.

Instead of printing only true or false, the system should produce a richer result:

print Valid Anagram if both strings are anagrams
otherwise print Invalid Anagram
then print the frequency of each character in sorted order for both strings
Input format :
The first line contains string s
The second line contains string t
Output format :
First line: print Valid Anagram or Invalid Anagram
Second line: print S: followed by the character frequencies of string s in sorted character order
Third line: print T: followed by the character frequencies of string t in sorted character order

Code constraints :
1 <= len(s), len(t) <= 5 * 10^4
s and t consist of lowercase English letters only

Sample test cases :
Input 1 :
anagram
nagaram
Output 1 :
Valid Anagram
S: a:3 g:1 m:1 n:1 r:1
T: a:3 g:1 m:1 n:1 r:1

Input 2 :
rat
car
Output 2 :
Invalid Anagram
S: a:1 r:1 t:1
T: a:1 c:1 r:1

Solution:


// You are using GCC
#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main(){
    
   string s;
   string t;
   
   cin>>s>>t;
   
   map<char,int>freq1;
   map<char,int>freq2;
   
  for(char c:s){
      freq1[c]++;
  }
  
  for(char c:t){
      freq2[c]++;
  }
  
  if(freq1 == freq2){
      cout<<"Valid anagram";
  }
  else
  {
      cout<<"Invalid anagram";
  }
  
  cout<<"\nS:"<<endl;
  
  for(auto c:freq1){
      cout<<c.first<<" : "<<c.second<<endl;
  }
  cout<<"T:"<<endl;
  
  for(auto c:freq2){
      cout<<c.first<<" : "<<c.second<<endl;
  }
  
}
